    <h2>Signs Your LG Dryer Heating Element Has Failed</h2>

    <p>The heating element is a coiled wire resistance heater. When it fails, heat stops entirely or becomes inconsistent. Here's what we see most often on service calls across LA and Orange County:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Dryer runs but clothes come out cold or damp</strong> — the most obvious sign; the drum spins normally but generates no heat</li>
      <li><strong>Takes 2–3 cycles to dry one load</strong> — element partially failed, producing weak heat</li>
      <li><strong>d80, d90, or d95 error codes</strong> — restricted airflow from a clogged vent can overheat and burn out the element</li>
      <li><strong>Burning smell before the dryer stopped heating</strong> — element wire broke under load</li>
      <li><strong>Dryer trips the breaker</strong> — element shorted to the housing</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Why LG Dryer Heating Elements Fail</h2>

    <p>In our experience servicing LG dryers across Los Angeles and Orange County, element failure rarely happens in isolation. The three most common root causes:</p>

    <h3>Clogged Dryer Vent</h3>
    <p>This is the #1 cause we see. When airflow is restricted, the heating chamber overheats and the element burns out prematurely. A d80 or d90 error code before the heat failure is a strong indicator. We check and clean the vent on every service call.</p>

    <h3>Failed Thermal Fuse</h3>
    <p>The thermal fuse is a one-time safety device that blows when the dryer overheats. When the fuse blows, it cuts power to the heating element. Many homeowners replace only the fuse — the dryer works briefly, then fails again because the underlying overheating issue wasn't fixed. We always diagnose the root cause, not just the symptom.</p>

    <h3>Normal Wear After 7–10 Years</h3>
    <p>LG heating elements (OEM part 5301EL1001J on most electric models) last 7–10 years under normal use. After that, the resistance wire fatigues and breaks. Standard replacement — no secondary cause needed.</p>

    <h2>OEM vs Aftermarket Heating Elements</h2>

    <p>We use only genuine LG OEM heating elements — part 5301EL1001J for most electric models. Aftermarket elements are available for $35–$50 online, but we've seen them fail within months and cause secondary thermostat damage. An OEM element costs more upfront but is built to the exact resistance and temperature tolerances of your specific LG dryer model. It also keeps your manufacturer warranty intact.</p>

